Here's a summary to add to your notes about what we covered:

Shuffling, Mean & Standard Deviation
Shuffling
Purpose: Makes data fair and prevents bias
Seed: Makes results reproducible (same random order every time)
Method: rng.permutation(X.shape[0]) creates shuffled indices
Important: Apply same indices to both X and y to keep (feature, target) pairs together
Mean & Standard Deviation
Mean: Average value of each feature across all samples
Standard Deviation: How spread out values are from the mean
axis=0: Compute down rows → per column (per feature statistics)
Why We Need Standardization
Different feature scales: Income (~0-15), Population (~3-35682), Age (~1-52)
Gradient descent problems:
Large features → huge gradients
Small features → tiny gradients
Unbalanced optimization
Solution: Standardize all features to mean=0, std=1
Formula: (X - mean) / std
Critical Rule
Calculate mean/std from TRAIN data only
Apply same statistics to both train and test
Never use test data statistics - this would be "data leakage"
Results
After standardization: All features have mean≈0, std=1
Benefits: Balanced gradients, faster convergence, consistent learning rate

np.hstack([np.ones((X_train.shape[0], 1)), X_train]) adds a bias column to your data.



Breaking it down:

np.ones((X_train.shape[0], 1)): Creates a column of ones
X_train.shape[0] = 16512 (number of samples)
So it creates: [[1], [1], [1], ..., [1]] (16512 rows, 1 column)
X_train: Your standardized features (16512 rows, 8 columns)
np.hstack([A, B]): Horizontal stack - joins arrays side by side
example:
Before: X_train.shape = (16512, 8)
After:  X_train.shape = (16512, 9)

New structure:
[[1, feature1, feature2, ..., feature8],  # Sample 1
 [1, feature1, feature2, ..., feature8],  # Sample 2
 ...
 [1, feature1, feature2, ..., feature8]]  # Sample 16512

 Yes, exactly! The bias column provides the intercept term.

How it works:

Bias column: [1, 1, 1, ..., 1] (all ones)
This gets multiplied by θ₀ (theta_0) in the linear regression formula
Formula: y = θ₀*1 + θ₁*x₁ + θ₂*x₂ + ... + θ₈*x₈
What this means:

θ₀ is the intercept (where the line crosses the y-axis when all features = 0)
The bias column of ones ensures θ₀ is always included in the prediction
Without bias: y = θ₁*x₁ + θ₂*x₂ + ... (must pass through origin)
With bias: y = θ₀ + θ₁*x₁ + θ₂*x₂ + ... (can shift up/down)

num_iters controls how many times gradient descent updates theta.

Why you need num_iters:
Gradual improvement: Each iteration makes theta slightly better
Convergence: Need multiple steps to reach the optimal minimum
Stopping point: Otherwise gradient descent would run forever

What convergence means:

Found optimal theta: Further iterations won't improve much
Model learned: Parameters are at the best possible values
Ready to use: Can now make predictions on test data
If not converged:
Cost still decreasing significantly
Might need more iterations
Or adjust learning rate


